place.name: WEYBOURNE
place.gazetteerText: WEYBOURNE, a parish, with a village, in Erpingham district, Norfolk; on the coast, 3¾ miles NE of Holt, and 12½ ENE of Walsingham r. station. It has a post-office under Thetford, and a coastguard station; and it carries on malting, brewing, fishing, and fish-curing. Acres, 1,680; of which 80 are water. Real property, £1, 843. Pop., 285. Houses, 69. The manor belongs to the Earl of Orford. An Augustinian friary was founded here in the time of King John, and has left some remains. The living is a donative in the diocese of Norwich. Value, £50. Patron, the Earl of Orford. The church is later English. (In 1870-72, John Marius Wilson's Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales)
